I want to congratulate Andrew Sharp and Ben Golliver, the hosts of Greatest=
 of All Talk ( https://goat.passport.online/member ) , for reaching 400 epi=
sodes; the last 50 or so have been a part of the Stratechery bundle (althou=
gh all of them are available for subscribers), and it=E2=80=99s great to ha=
ve them on board. And, if you have any passing interest in the NBA, or are =
just looking for a podcast with great chemistry that rewards regular listen=
ing, then check out the link at the bottom of this email.

On to the Update:

Adobe Max
---------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-10-10/adobe-r=
eleases-new-ai-models-aimed-at-improved-graphic-design ) :

Adobe Inc. announced new versions of its generative artificial intelligence=
 model, Firefly, promising higher-quality images and the ability to produce=
 new types of media. The new edition of its AI model was trained on about 7=
0% more images, which should improve the system=E2=80=99s ability to create=
 photo-realistic images and bring it closer to the output of competitors, s=
aid Alexandru Costin, Adobe vice president of generative AI. The latest ver=
sion will also include new ways to control and prompt the AI generation, su=
ch as uploading an image to replicate its style. Adobe will keep an interna=
l record of the reference images that are uploaded in order to protect arti=
sts from infringement, Costin said. The company has branded Firefly as =E2=
=80=9Ccommercially safe,=E2=80=9D saying it will back up customers who face=
 copyright claims in court.

Adobe, the longtime creative software leader, is building AI models trained=
 mostly on its vast library of stock photography, and is trying to gain an =
edge over startups like OpenAI by integrating the new technology into indus=
try-standard products such as Photoshop. After making the new AI tools gene=
rally available, Adobe increased the prices of its software last month. The=
 company introduced the latest versions of its AI tools Tuesday in conjunct=
ion with its annual user conference in Los Angeles.

I titled this section =E2=80=9CAdobe Max=E2=80=9D, but this post from Bloom=
berg is all about Firefly; it=E2=80=99s fine, because that=E2=80=99s exactl=
y what Adobe Max was all about. Adobe demonstrated Firefly in Photoshop, in=
 Illustrator, and previewed Firefly for audio, video, and 3D models. Small =
wonder that Adobe CEO Shantanu Narayen took care in his opening remarks of =
the keynote ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D1tbrJNP5Cjk ) to emphasize =
human creativity:

( https://videopress.com/embed/bmgZ8wcd?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

As I think the last few years it=E2=80=99s amazing to reflect on the increa=
sing important role that creativity has played in our daily lives. In helpi=
ng us cope, come together, and engage with the world around us. Just think =
about the interactions we have with each other, how we work, how we=E2=80=
=99re entertained: our lives are becoming increasingly digital, and we=E2=
=80=99re turning to creative differentiation to help us stand out as well a=
s make choices. People are creating more than ever before, flooding every s=
urface, every channel, and every medium with their creativity=E2=80=A6Digit=
al is transforming every aspect of our lives and how we engage with the wor=
ld=E2=80=99s information. Artificial Intelligence is accelerating this shif=
t, and offers the promise and potential to make us even more creative, even=
 more productive, and more successful.

This was a theme that was repeated throughout the presentation: AI helps wi=
th exploration, productivity, creative control, and community:

Adobe's AI focuses ( https://www.youtube.com/live/1tbrJNP5Cjk?si=3DyRWQh0sS=
n0Mh78q7&t=3D1595 )

Notice that each of those are an optimistic framing of what could be a dyst=
opian vision for AI-generated content: isolated experiences (not community)=
, served to you by a faceless AI (no control), helping you wile away the ti=
me (not explore) because you have nothing better to do (your productivity i=
s no longer needed). It=E2=80=99s the question of whether AI is a tool, or =
an omniscient opiate, and it certainly is in Adobe=E2=80=99s interest to fr=
ame it as the former, while ensuring it creates the tools to create the lat=
ter.

Narayen said towards the end of his remarks:

( https://videopress.com/embed/QkRwv1MQ?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

We=E2=80=99ve really challenged our product teams to integrate our generati=
ve models seamlessly into the apps and experiences that you are using every=
 day so that we can bring these new innovations to life. Generative Fill, G=
enerative Re-color, and a lot of the other product features that you=E2=80=
=99re going to see today are the result of our Photoshop, Illustrator, Expr=
ess, Firefly, Premiere Pro, Acrobat, InDesign teams working tirelessly to d=
eliver on this potential for every one of you.

You=E2=80=99ve come to expect that Adobe products now have power, precision=
, and control to serve your most exacting needs, because we know that gener=
ative technology is not an end, but it=E2=80=99s an ingredient in your crea=
tive process. It=E2=80=99s an on-ramp, so we=E2=80=99re focusing sure that =
we integrate it directly into your workflows to fuel your creativity and de=
livery the power and precision that you expect from us. We will continuousl=
y bring Firefly-powered features into more Creative Cloud, Document Cloud, =
and Experience Cloud apps and workflows in unique ways.

That, I would note, is more than optimism about AI: it=E2=80=99s optimism a=
bout what AI can do for Adobe=E2=80=99s strategic positioning.

Figma and Firefly
-----------------

Again from Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-10-16/i=
phone-15-china-sales-disappoint-as-huawei-rises-jefferies-says ) , a couple=
 of days after Max ended:

Adobe Inc.=E2=80=99s proposed $20 billion acquisition of Figma was a corner=
stone of the creative giant=E2=80=99s plan to become cool again. But more t=
han a year after the deal for the digital-design startup was announced, it =
has stalled due to regulatory challenges, and the software company=E2=80=99=
s attention has moved on to the next big thing =E2=80=94 artificial intelli=
gence.

Adobe=E2=80=99s focus at its annual conference in Los Angeles this week was=
 on new generative artificial intelligence features in signature products l=
ike Photoshop. There were no mentions of Figma during keynote speeches, and=
 only one reference during an hourslong investor briefing. The design start=
up had no presence on the exhibition floor. That=E2=80=99s a stark contrast=
 from last year=E2=80=99s event, when Figma Chief Executive Officer Dylan F=
ield joined Adobe=E2=80=99s main keynote presentation to talk about future =
product integrations and fist-bump Adobe Chief Strategy Officer Scott Belsk=
y, an architect of the deal. Field also joined last year=E2=80=99s investor=
 briefing, where the startup=E2=80=99s name was uttered 40 times.

It=E2=80=99s been over a year since the acquisition was announced, and eigh=
t months since Bloomberg reported ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles=
/2023-02-23/doj-preparing-suit-to-block-adobe-s-20-billion-deal-for-figma )=
 that the Justice Department was preparing a lawsuit to block the acquisiti=
on; the EU announced a Phase 2 investigation ( https://www.bloomberg.com/ne=
ws/articles/2023-08-07/adobe-s-20-billion-figma-takeover-hit-by-in-depth-eu=
-probe ) into the deal in August. Both threaten the March 2024 deadline for=
 the deal to close, and certainly raise the question if the goal is simply =
to run out the clock (something Microsoft complained about vociferously in =
terms of the Activision review). Regardless, one can understand why Adobe m=
ight want to avoid the topic at the developer conference.

At the same time, I think that the emergence of AI and the aggressive way t=
hat Adobe is integrating Firefly into its products significantly strengthen=
s the company=E2=80=99s strategic positioning, even if the deal were blocke=
d. This is important because the Figma acquisition never made sense financi=
ally; the goal was strategic, for reasons I explained in an Update at the t=
ime ( https://stratechery.com/2022/adobe-acquires-figma-figmas-disruption-t=
he-figma-os/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnB=
hc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9yd=
C5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJo=
dHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIyL2Fkb2JlLWFjcXVpcmVzLWZpZ21hLWZpZ21hcy1=
kaXNydXB0aW9uLXRoZS1maWdtYS1vcy8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcwMDE0MDU4MCwiaWF0IjoxNjk3NT=
Q4NTgwLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6I=
mZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVt=
ZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.prQy=
G9F-yDpXEMOC3vRs7sCoFwrVmwa3gZv302ZJQ-hiGezMpkQKbgfP2KKnlS62YBqr1Tn3YUi3ocM=
LpnhSk58Jma5QR_atoWgjE8uzD5Jmm5f1MwLmxuKGuDySOqeY-2mKYKzPRQmHbLhnRWIJL_zFVC=
KJUuBRQJW1QvCcnFctBlMGeeOuFF43dxu293OklF9DpoLskFp8udjgv5X1t57hJr-ZtO94oyBob=
NHXGaPbgrqefphMBgUl0_4D-Mx9YQ8lQKR4ch-_-J_IPUaZi-KSBfyFBZAg2y6CDpgV-lBnikEK=
8UUv6wcXubHrCnBMiKfj423vV9etW2AgUvftDw ) :

Figma=E2=80=99s photo-editing tools are rudimentary and not remotely compet=
itive with Photoshop; it=E2=80=99s vector editing tools are a bit more adva=
nced but still nowhere near the capability of Illustrator. An app maker may=
 use Figma to place a logo or photo in the application, but the actual crea=
tion of that logo or photo still happens in Adobe=E2=80=99s products. Sure,=
 XD is getting killed by Figma, but no one ever subscribed to Creative Clou=
d for XD; you just used it because it was there.

Here is the problem, though: to the extent that Adobe=E2=80=99s products we=
re being used as part of a Figma workflow was the extent to which Adobe was=
 slowly but surely losing control of its long-term relevance. Figma could, =
for example, start investing much more heavily in its photo editing or illu=
stration capabilities, rendering Adobe=E2=80=99s products increasingly unne=
cessary. What is more threatening is Figma=E2=80=99s platform capabilities:=
 3rd-party developers can build plugins for Figma that make it possible to =
easily add the sort of editing capabilities that Figma itself lacks, for ex=
ample. The introduction to the company=E2=80=99s API states ( https://www.f=
igma.com/developers/api#intro ) :

The Figma API supports read access and interactions with Figma files. This =
gives you the ability to view and extract any objects or layers, and their =
properties, so you can render them as images outside of Figma. You can then=
 present your designs, connect them to other applications, or use them to e=
xpand on your vision. Future versions of the API will unlock even greater f=
unctionality around Files.

This is a world where Figma is the operating system for design, and applica=
tions like Photoshop and Illustrator are reduced to plugins, and increasing=
ly commoditized. That, by extension, is exactly what Adobe is buying: contr=
ol of the key integration point in the design pipeline, and, one would assu=
me, a favored position for Adobe=E2=80=99s own apps in that pipeline.

Adobe did, of course, survive for a long time as an app in a world dominate=
d by operating systems from other companies; those were the days of desktop=
 computers, though, where desktop publishing was the job-to-be-done, and on=
e that could be done entirely within Adobe=E2=80=99s suite of apps. The cha=
llenge is that Figma is on pace to be the operating system of design for di=
gital applications and websites: actually building the latter is considerab=
ly more complex than sending a PDF off to a printer, which means that you n=
eed more tools than those offered by Adobe, which undergirds the long-term =
risk of just being a very-expensive yet increasingly-commoditized part of t=
he value chain.

If Narayen is right, though, that AI will not be a standalone entity of its=
 own, but rather an essential part of the creative value chain, then Adobe=
=E2=80=99s move to deeply integrate AI into its apps de-commoditizes them a=
nd provides a point of integration in that value chain. Sure, you could gen=
erate something in Dall-E or MidJourney, and then import it into a Photosho=
p alternative, but your workflow is going to be a lot better if you just us=
e Photoshop (and get all of the corporate niceties Adobe provides, like gua=
rantees against copyright infringement ( https://www.fastcompany.com/909065=
60/adobe-feels-so-confident-its-firefly-generative-ai-wont-breach-copyright=
-itll-cover-your-legal-bills ) ). That integration, by extension, means tha=
t it will fall on Figma to make sure that Photoshop et al work well with Fi=
gma, just as Apple and Microsoft used to have to bend over backwards to acc=
ommodate Adobe=E2=80=99s desktop apps.

I=E2=80=99m sure Adobe would still prefer to complete the acquisition; Figm=
a could, for example, help integrate alternative generative AI tools with a=
lternative editors, illustrators, etc. It=E2=80=99s definitely better strat=
egically to ensure you are the favored choice (and bundled!) than to have t=
o fight for it. Adobe is, though, much better equipped for that fight today=
 than they were when they made the Figma acquisition in the first place.

The Icon of Transparency
------------------------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2023/10/10/23911381/adobe-ai-gene=
rated-content-symbol-watermark ) :

Adobe and other companies have established a symbol that can be attached to=
 content alongside metadata, establishing its provenance, including whether=
 it was made with AI tools. The symbol, which Adobe calls an =E2=80=9Cicon =
of transparency,=E2=80=9D can be added via Adobe=E2=80=99s photo and video =
editing platforms like Photoshop or Premiere and eventually Microsoft=E2=80=
=99s Bing Image Generator. It will be added to the metadata of images, vide=
os, and PDFs to announce who owns and created the data. When viewers look a=
t a photo online, they can hover over the mark, and it will open a dropdown=
 that includes information about its ownership, the AI tool used to make it=
, and other details about the media=E2=80=99s production.

Andy Parsons, senior director of Adobe=E2=80=99s Content Authenticity Initi=
ative, tells The Verge that the symbol acts as a =E2=80=9Cnutrition label=
=E2=80=9D of sorts, telling people the provenance of the media. The presenc=
e of the symbol is meant to encourage the tagging of AI-generated data, as =
Parsons said it creates more transparency into how content was created=E2=
=80=A6While the small symbol is visible in the image, the information and t=
he symbol are also embedded in the metadata, so it will not be Photoshopped=
 out. Adobe says other companies in the C2PA will begin implementing the ne=
w symbol in the coming months. Microsoft, for example, has been using a cus=
tom digital watermark in content created with its Bing Image Generator but =
will be using the new icon soon. Companies and users are not required to ad=
opt the symbol.

Here=E2=80=99s the symbol:

The Icon of Transparency ( https://contentcredentials.org/ )

This symbol and the associated metadata is, as the The Verge notes, being p=
ositioned as something that ought be added to AI-generated images. What I t=
hink is smart, though, is that the symbol and metadata itself is actually n=
ot explicitly about AI: you could also use the symbol and metadata to decla=
re that an image was of human provenance. This is important because I think=
 that to the extent this symbol succeeds it will be used for exactly that: =
identifying what is actually from humans.

Think about it in terms of the marginal cost of creating content: it takes =
a human time and effort to make an image. Yes, there are a lot of humans, a=
nd yes, those humans have a head start in content. The marginal cost for an=
 AI to generate images, though, is so drastically lower that it seems inevi=
table that AI-generated content will come to dominate. Moreover, there will=
 be models other than Adobe=E2=80=99s or Microsoft=E2=80=99s, which again, =
only apply a label optionally.

What will be rare is human-content and, more importantly, it will be import=
ant to the humans that create it to label it as such. That is where marks l=
ike this will matter more (and, I might note, where a technology that guara=
ntees authenticity via digital scarcity would be quite useful =E2=80=94 yes=
, this is a blockchain reference).

